You can solve this problem by writing a function that uses the `Statistics` package to calculate basic statistical properties of the given data. In this case, we are interested in finding the mean (average), maximum and minimum values.

Here is a possible solution:

```julia
using Statistics

function weather_data_analyzer(temps)
    if isempty(temps)  # check if list is empty
        return (average=nothing, max=nothing, min=nothing, trend=nothing)
    else
        avg = mean(temps)  # compute average
        maxi = maximum(temps)  # find the max temperature
        mini = minimum(temps)  # find the min temperature

        if avg > maxi  # check trend (increasing)
            return (average=avg, max=maxi, min=mini, trend=:increasing)
        elseif avg < mini  # decreasing
            return (average=avg, max=maxi, min=mini, trend=:decreasing)
        else  # stable (when average equals to the temperature with maximum value)
            return (average=avg, max=maxi, min=mini, trend=:stable)
        end
    end
end
```

This function first checks if the given list of daily temperatures is empty. If it is, it returns a named tuple with all values set to `nothing`. If not, it calculates the average (mean), maximum and minimum temperatures, and then determines which trend is predominant - increasing, decreasing or stable based on these calculated values. It then constructs and returns a named tuple in the form `(; key1=value1,key2=value2)`.
